{
    "id": "math",
    "lang": "en-us",
    "name": "Math",
    "description": "Your number toolbox: round, clamp, smoothly blend between values, pick random numbers, work with angles, and more — with plain examples for each.",
    "link": "/docs/uniscript/en-us/math",
    "tags": [
        "uniscript",
        "math",
        "numbers",
        "random",
        "lerp",
        "clamp"
    ],
    "previous": {
        "name": "",
        "link": ""
    },
    "next": {
        "name": "TypeUtil",
        "link": "/docs/uniscript/en-us/typeutil"
    },
    "content": [
        {
            "id": "block-001",
            "tag": "h1",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Math"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-002",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`Math` is your **number toolbox**. Any time you need to round a value, keep a number inside a range, fade smoothly from one value to another, pick a random number, or work with angles — there's a ready-made tool here so you don't have to reinvent it."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-003",
            "tag": "note",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Every tool here is called as `Math.SomeTool(...)` — you don't need a character or object first. For example: `float root = Math.Sqrt(9.0);` gives `3.0`."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-004",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Rounding and whole numbers"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-005",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "These turn a decimal number into a whole one, or tell you its sign:"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-006",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Tool",
                "What it does",
                "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
                [
                    "`Round(f)`",
                    "Rounds to the nearest whole number.",
                    "`Math.Round(2.6)` → `3.0`"
                ],
                [
                    "`Floor(f)`",
                    "Rounds **down**.",
                    "`Math.Floor(2.9)` → `2.0`"
                ],
                [
                    "`Ceil(f)`",
                    "Rounds **up**.",
                    "`Math.Ceil(2.1)` → `3.0`"
                ],
                [
                    "`RoundToInt(f)` / `FloorToInt(f)` / `CeilToInt(f)`",
                    "Same as above but give back a whole `int` you can count with.",
                    "`Math.FloorToInt(2.9)` → `2`"
                ],
                [
                    "`Abs(f)`",
                    "Removes the minus sign (absolute value).",
                    "`Math.Abs(-5.0)` → `5.0`"
                ],
                [
                    "`Sign(f)`",
                    "Tells direction: `-1` if negative, `1` if positive.",
                    "`Math.Sign(-8.0)` → `-1.0`"
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-007",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Keeping a number in range"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-008",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`Clamp` is one of the most useful tools in any game — it stops a value from going too high or too low. A health bar that can never exceed 100 or drop below 0 is a perfect example:"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-009",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "// Health can never go below 0 or above 100.",
                "health = Math.Clamp(health - damage, 0.0, 100.0);"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-010",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Tool",
                "What it does"
            ],
            "rows": [
                [
                    "`Clamp(value, min, max)`",
                    "Forces `value` to stay between `min` and `max`."
                ],
                [
                    "`Clamp01(value)`",
                    "Forces `value` to stay between `0` and `1` (a handy shortcut)."
                ],
                [
                    "`Max(a, b)` / `Min(a, b)`",
                    "Returns the bigger / smaller of two decimal numbers."
                ],
                [
                    "`MaxInt(a, b)` / `MinInt(a, b)`",
                    "Same, but for whole numbers (`int`)."
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-011",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Smoothly blending between values"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-012",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "**Interpolation** means \"find a value partway between two others\". It's how you make things fade, ease, and glide instead of snapping. The star of the show is `Lerp`."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-013",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`Math.Lerp(a, b, t)` gives you a point between `a` and `b`, where `t` is how far along (between `0` and `1`). `t = 0` returns `a`, `t = 1` returns `b`, and `t = 0.5` returns the exact middle."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-014",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "Math.Lerp(0.0, 100.0, 0.0);   // 0   (the start)",
                "Math.Lerp(0.0, 100.0, 0.5);   // 50  (the middle)",
                "Math.Lerp(0.0, 100.0, 1.0);   // 100 (the end)",
                "",
                "// Smoothly slide a value toward a target a little each frame.",
                "current = Math.Lerp(current, target, 0.1);"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-015",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Tool",
                "What it does"
            ],
            "rows": [
                [
                    "`Lerp(a, b, t)`",
                    "Blend between `a` and `b`. `t` is clamped to `0`–`1`."
                ],
                [
                    "`LerpUnclamped(a, b, t)`",
                    "Like `Lerp`, but allows `t` outside `0`–`1` to overshoot."
                ],
                [
                    "`InverseLerp(a, b, value)`",
                    "The opposite: given a `value`, tells you its `t` (how far between `a` and `b` it sits). Great for progress bars."
                ],
                [
                    "`SmoothStep(from, to, t)`",
                    "Like `Lerp` but eases in and out for an even softer feel."
                ],
                [
                    "`MoveTowards(current, target, maxDelta)`",
                    "Steps `current` toward `target` by at most `maxDelta` — never overshoots."
                ],
                [
                    "`SmoothDamp(...)`",
                    "Spring-like smoothing toward a target (see note below)."
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-016",
            "tag": "tip",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "To make a blend feel the same on every device, scale your step by frame time: `Math.Lerp(current, target, Time.DeltaTime() * 5.0)`. See [Time](/docs/uniscript/en-us/time) for why."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-017",
            "tag": "note",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`SmoothDamp(current, target, currentVelocity, smoothTime, maxSpeed, deltaTime)` returns a `vector3` where the **X** value is the new number and the **Y** value is the updated velocity — feed that velocity back in next frame to keep the spring going."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-018",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Random numbers"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-019",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Randomness makes games feel alive — random drop positions, random enemy choices, random damage. `Math.Random(min, max)` gives a number in the range you ask for."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-020",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "// A random decimal between 0 and 1 (e.g. a chance roll).",
                "float chance = Math.Random(0.0, 1.0);",
                "if (chance < 0.25) { /* 25% of the time... */ }",
                "",
                "// A random whole number from 1 to 6 (like a dice roll).",
                "int dice = Math.Random(1, 6);"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-021",
            "tag": "note",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Passing **decimals** (`0.0, 1.0`) gives a decimal result; passing **whole numbers** (`1, 6`) gives a whole-number result. Call `Math.InitSeed(seed)` once if you want the same sequence of random numbers every play (useful for testing)."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-022",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Angles and trigonometry"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-023",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "These help with circular motion, aiming, and waves. `Sin` and `Cos` are especially handy for things that bob, sway, or orbit."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-024",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "// Make an object bob up and down forever.",
                "float bob = Math.Sin(Time.GameTime() * 2.0) * 0.5;",
                "// ...then add 'bob' to the object's Y position each frame."
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-025",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Tool",
                "What it does"
            ],
            "rows": [
                [
                    "`Sin(f)` / `Cos(f)` / `Tan(f)`",
                    "The basic trig functions (angle in **radians**)."
                ],
                [
                    "`Asin(f)` / `Acos(f)` / `Atan(f)`",
                    "The reverse trig functions."
                ],
                [
                    "`Atan2(y, x)`",
                    "The angle pointing toward the direction `(x, y)` — perfect for aiming."
                ],
                [
                    "`DeltaAngle(current, target)`",
                    "The shortest turn (in degrees) between two angles."
                ],
                [
                    "`LerpAngle(a, b, t)` / `MoveTowardsAngle(...)`",
                    "Blend or step between angles, taking the short way around."
                ],
                [
                    "`Deg2Rad()` / `Rad2Deg()`",
                    "Convert between degrees and radians: `angle * Math.Deg2Rad()`."
                ],
                [
                    "`Approximately(a, b)`",
                    "`true` if two decimals are *almost* equal (decimals are rarely exactly equal)."
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-026",
            "tag": "important",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`Sin`, `Cos`, and `Tan` expect angles in **radians**, not degrees. If you're thinking in degrees, multiply first: `Math.Sin(degrees * Math.Deg2Rad())`."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-027",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Powers, roots, and logarithms"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-028",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Tool",
                "What it does",
                "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
                [
                    "`Pow(f, p)`",
                    "Raise `f` to the power `p`.",
                    "`Math.Pow(2.0, 3.0)` → `8.0`"
                ],
                [
                    "`Sqrt(f)`",
                    "Square root.",
                    "`Math.Sqrt(16.0)` → `4.0`"
                ],
                [
                    "`Exp(power)` / `Ln(f)`",
                    "Natural exponential and logarithm.",
                    "—"
                ],
                [
                    "`Log(f, p)` / `Log10(f)`",
                    "Logarithm with a chosen base / base 10.",
                    "—"
                ],
                [
                    "`NextPowerOfTwo(v)` / `ClosestPowerOfTwo(v)` / `IsPowerOfTwo(v)`",
                    "Helpers for powers of two (2, 4, 8, 16, ...).",
                    "—"
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-029",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Loops, waves, and noise"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-030",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Tool",
                "What it does"
            ],
            "rows": [
                [
                    "`Repeat(t, length)`",
                    "Wraps `t` so it always stays between `0` and `length` (like a looping clock)."
                ],
                [
                    "`PingPong(t, length)`",
                    "Bounces `t` back and forth between `0` and `length` — great for patrols."
                ],
                [
                    "`PerlinNoise(x, y)`",
                    "Smooth, natural-looking randomness (range `0`–`1`). Good for wind, terrain, wobble."
                ],
                [
                    "`Perlin1D(x)` / `Perlin3D(x, y, z)`",
                    "Noise in 1 or 3 dimensions (range `-1`–`1`)."
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-031",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Constant values"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-032",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "These take no input and just hand back a fixed value: `Math.PI()` (~3.14159), `Math.Epsilon()` (a tiny number close to zero), `Math.Infinity()`, and `Math.NegativeInfinity()`."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-033",
            "tag": "note",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Even though these are constants, they are written as **methods** with parentheses: `Math.PI()`, not `Math.PI`."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-034",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Full tool reference"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-035",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Returns",
                "Method",
                "Parameters"
            ],
            "rows": [
                ["`float`", "`Abs`", "`float f`"],
                ["`float`", "`Acos`", "`float f`"],
                ["`bool`", "`Approximately`", "`float a, float b`"],
                ["`float`", "`Asin`", "`float f`"],
                ["`float`", "`Atan`", "`float f`"],
                ["`float`", "`Atan2`", "`float y, float x`"],
